Sub-Saharan African Stocks: BAT Kenya, Kenya Commercial and NIC Bank Move

-- B y   S a r a h   M c G r e g o r
-- 
2011-02-24T14:02:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-24/sub-saharan-african-stocks-bat-kenya-kenya-commercial-and-nic-bank-move.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index fell the most this month, retreating 1.8 percent to
26,234.64 by 2:12 p.m. in Lagos.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index declined for a seventh day, the
longest streak of losses in almost a year, losing 0.2 percent to
2,029.25 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis . Kenya’s All-Share
Index climbed for a third day, adding 0.2 percent to 77.32 by
the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index climbed the most since Feb. 3, rising 1.1 percent to
1,053.4 by 1:14 p.m. in Accra, while Namibia’s FTSE  Namibia
Overall Index  was little changed at 876.8 by 3:13 p.m. in
Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    British American Tobacco Kenya Ltd . (BATK KN), East
Africa’s biggest cigarette maker, climbed to the highest since
Nov. 24, adding 7 shillings, or 2.6 percent to 281 shillings.
Profit jumped 20 percent to 1.77 billion shillings ($22 million)
in the year through December as domestic and export volumes
increased, the company said in a statement after the market
closed yesterday.    Kenya Commercial Bank Ltd . (KNCB KN), the nation’s fifth-
biggest lender, advanced the most in a week, rising 25 cents, or
1.1 percent, to 23.25 shillings. Net income increased 76 percent
to 7.18 billion shillings in the 12 months through December from
a year earlier, Chairman Peter Muthoka told reporters in Nairobi
today.    NIC Bank Ltd . (NICB KN), a Kenyan lender, gained for a
third day, adding 50 cents, or 1 percent, to 52 shillings.
Profit rose 71 percent to 1.86 billion shillings in the year
through December as income from lending grew, the company said
today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
